And there are over a hundred
Apple engineers here this week,

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:16.200
a thousand sorry, Apple engineers here
this week to help you.

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:19.310
So there's a lot of
Apple folks floating around.

00:02:19.310 --> 00:02:22.470
Grab them, make use of them,
and we hope you have a

00:02:22.550 --> 00:02:24.460
great week here at WWDC.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:29.250
Now, we're going to talk
about three things today.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:36.330
You know, if the hardware is the brain
and the sinew of our products,

00:02:36.390 --> 00:02:40.520
the software in them is their soul.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:44.700
And today we are going
to talk about software.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:48.250
We've got some great stuff to talk about.

00:02:48.250 --> 00:02:49.480
OS X Lion, the

00:02:50.390 --> 00:02:56.500
IOS5 and some kind of
interesting new cloud stuff.

00:02:56.750 --> 00:02:59.880
So, let's start with Lion.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.230
To tell us all about Lion,
I'm going to ask two of my colleagues,

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:08.250
Phil Schiller and Craig Federighi,
to take us through Lion and

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:09.100
give us some demos.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:09.590
Phil?

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:17.710
Thank you, Steve.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:24.830
Oh, good morning, everyone.

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:27.640
How you doing?

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:28.580
Yeah.

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:29.910
Come on, energy in the room.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:32.730
This is the Developer Conference.

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:34.500
and more.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:39.500
I am really honored to be the
first to present to you the

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.060
first of our new products today.

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:43.620
And this product is all about the Mac.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:46.720
And the Mac is doing incredibly well.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:50.760
Our customer base continues
to grow at a tremendous pace.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:57.400
We now have over 54 million active
Mac users around the world and growing.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:00.790
The customers love the products
and press and analysts have really

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:03.480
incredible things to say about it.

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:05.380
Things like this from All Things D.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:07.260
There's really no other way to say this.

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:09.850
The Mac is kicking ass.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:17.300
Now, that's really nice,
but what did John mean?

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:19.240
Well, this is what he means.

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:22.280
The last quarter,
the PC market actually shrank year

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:27.190
over year 1%, while the MAC grew 28%.

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.580
In my book, that's an ass kicking.

00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:35.350
Now,
lest you think this is an aberration,

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:39.780
the Mac has outgrown the industry
every quarter for the past five years.

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:42.440
It is going so strong,
and it's because the

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:43.690
products are incredible.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:45.910
Products like the new MacBook Air.

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:49.100
It's beautiful, it's thin, it's light,
it's fast.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:51.370
The whole PC industry wants to copy it.

00:04:51.370 --> 00:04:54.070
But as you know, we've been leading in
notebooks for a while.

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:56.830
We were the first to really
drive the majority of our

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:58.950
PC business to a notebook business.

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:00.880
And it's almost three quarters of the
Mac business that's been doing that.

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:03.020
We are going to talk about the facts we

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:08.350
But whether you want a great new notebook
or a killer desktop with the new iMac,

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:11.150
these Macs are the best that we have
ever made in the history of Apple.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.950
And they're great not just
because of the hardware they run,

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:15.480
but because of the software.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.740
Mac OS X is the heart of the Mac.

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:22.720
And if you're keeping track,
you know we launched

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:24.590
Mac OS X 10 years ago.

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:27.490
We built it on a solid Unix foundation.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:30.720
We added to it the ease of
use and simplicity that we

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:32.670
know Apple's renowned for.

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:36.530
And we built into it amazing
technologies for all of our great

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:40.050
developers to make the world's
best applications to run on it.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:43.240
And for those of you who are
around and remember this,

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:47.600
this is what Mac OS X looked like
10 years ago when we launched it.

00:05:53.610 --> 00:05:56.300
It was a revolution in its day.

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:59.670
And over the last 10 years it's
evolved to become more refined,

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.500
more powerful,
more beautiful than ever before.

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:05.880
The Mac OS X is looking
incredibly strong.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.800
So where do we take it next?

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:12.480
Well, next up in OS X is Lion,
a major release with

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:15.300
over 250 new features.

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:17.540
And if you'd like,
we can go through every

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:18.710
one of them today.

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:22.030
Well I'd love to,
I'm told I only have enough time to

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:24.880
tell you about 10 key new features.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:26.930
So we'll really get into
10 awesome features.

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:31.100
First up, right into it, number one,
multi-touch gestures.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:34.370
One of the great things about
the Mac from the beginning was

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:37.430
that it ushered an era of a
graphic user interface with a

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:39.590
mouse and clicking and dragging.

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:42.830
But so much has changed
over the last 10 years.

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:46.290
We now build multi-touch trackpads
into all of our notebooks and

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:47.920
we offer them on our desktops.

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:50.190
We've learned a lot from iOS as well.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:53.250
So now Lion can count on multi-touch.

00:06:53.250 --> 00:06:55.610
From the beginning you
can have beautiful,

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:57.600
fluid, momentum-based scrolling.

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:02.030
You can have incredible multi-touch
taps to zoom in on stories or pictures.

00:07:02.030 --> 00:07:05.990
You can dynamically zoom with beautiful,
fluid pinch motions.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.320
You can swipe through your photographs,
your slides, your web page.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:13.830
All with an incredible physical
realism that's never been possible

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:15.780
with a PC operating system before.

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:18.590
And this has implications
across the system in a lot

00:07:18.590 --> 00:07:20.280
of little important areas.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:22.140
Here's a simple example.

00:07:22.210 --> 00:07:23.400
The scroll bar.

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:24.430
Why do we have scroll bars?

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:27.450
Scroll bars were there so you could
click with the mouse and drag and scroll.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:30.210
But now if you're pushing
your window with multi-touch,

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:31.310
you don't need them.

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:32.440
They can disappear.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.110
You can have a much more
beautiful reading environment.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:37.370
But when you go to scroll,
they magically appear,

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:39.620
give you a sense of place
and proportional size.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:40.320
And then disappear.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:42.420
They disappear when you don't need them.

00:07:42.550 --> 00:07:46.520
So multi-touch is now built throughout
the system in a very powerful way.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:50.740
Number two, full screen applications.

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:53.080
We've had some full screen
applications before and these are

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:54.400
really important for notebooks.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.870
11 inch and 13 inch where
you want to take advantage of

00:07:57.870 --> 00:07:59.400
every pixel on the display.

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:03.240
But developers have had to work
hard to make their applications hand

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:07.400
coded to do full screen applications,
including apps like iPhoto.

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:10.450
Well now with Lion we've built in
a standard method for developers

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:12.400
to create full screen applications.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:16.280
And it has a simple system control
in the top right so all users

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:19.400
know where to tap and then bring
their applications full screen.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:23.190
But this isn't full screen like
it was before because now you can

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:27.420
keep your application running full
screen with a simple swipe gesture,

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:29.520
get back to your desktop,
get something you need,

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:33.400
go back to your application,
never having left full screen.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:36.160
In fact you can have more than
one full screen application

00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:37.570
running at the same time.

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:40.470
So we've worked on a number of our
applications to bring them into

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:42.750
the new full screen mode of Lion.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:50.050
System applications like Safari, Mail,
iCal, iLife applications, iPhoto, iMovie,

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.560
GarageBand,
iWork with Keynote and Numbers and

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:55.840
Pages and all these applications
going full screen so you have a great

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:57.630
experience right out of the box.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:00.280
Here's an example of how it looks.

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:03.060
This is now running
full screen in Safari.

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:05.660
You can have a beautiful place
for viewing your documents and now

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:08.130
there's a new feature since we've
got all this extra room on the left

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:09.580
hand side called the reading list.

00:09:09.610 --> 00:09:11.790
Keep track of things you
want to get to later.

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:14.600
Here's iCal running full screen.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:18.170
Here's preview showing you PDF documents
running full screen so you can

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:21.590
just have a beautiful experience
like we've never had on a computer

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:23.840
before with full screen applications.

00:09:25.780 --> 00:09:26.700
Next feature.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:29.130
For many users,
this will be the best feature of Lion.

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:31.700
It's called Mission Control.

00:09:31.700 --> 00:09:34.230
Now,
we all like to run a lot of software.

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.480
At Apple,
we've created many features to help

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:38.440
customers find just what they need.

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.470
Expose for finding a document,
dashboard for getting at a quick widget,

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:45.170
spaces for organizing
your work environment,

00:09:45.170 --> 00:09:48.080
but didn't it all work
together in one unified way?

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:51.280
Well, now with Lion,
we've unified that with a simple

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.610
gesture to get into Mission Control.

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:57.160
And this is a bird's eye view of
everything going on in your system.

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:00.190
On the main window, well,
that's the current desktop you're working

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:03.710
on with all the documents now organized
by what application is running on them.

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:06.370
And you can tap on any document
and bring it to the front.

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:09.530
That's right there,
center for you to work on.

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:12.580
Up above are all your spaces.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:14.940
So you can have multiple desktops,
you can have multiple

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:17.900
full screen apps running,
get to any one with a single tap.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.940
And on the left of those spaces
is a new special one just

00:10:21.250 --> 00:10:23.000
for your dashboard widgets.

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:26.000
You can get to again with a single tap.

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:28.940
So that's mission control.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.180
What I'd like to do now
is before we move on,

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:33.730
have Craig Federighi come up and
give you a demo of these three

00:10:33.730 --> 00:10:35.140
new features all working together.

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:36.540
Craig?

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:37.620
Hello.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:39.290
Good morning.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:46.240
So let's take a look at Lion in action.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.540
And we're going to start with gestures.

00:10:48.540 --> 00:10:52.140
Great place to experience
gestures is here in Safari.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:54.890
The first thing you'll notice--

00:10:55.130 --> 00:10:56.330
Apparently something funny.

00:10:56.410 --> 00:11:01.380
Is that how simple this UI looks
because there are no scroll bars.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:03.250
It's a really clean look.

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:06.500
We don't need scroll bars anymore
because we can simply push

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:08.230
the content with our fingers.

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:11.540
We can flick and get momentum,
get a nice little bounce.

00:11:11.540 --> 00:11:14.800
The page feels really
alive beneath your fingers.

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:21.000
You can also expand your fingers
and fluidly zoom just like that.

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:24.380
Zoom out and you get
a nice little bounce.

00:11:25.900 --> 00:11:58.500
[Transcript missing]

00:11:58.710 --> 00:12:05.380
In fact, I can swipe through my entire
Safari browsing history just like that.

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.330
Really smooth.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:11.900
Next up,
I'd like to show you full screen apps.

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:14.700
I'm going to launch iPhoto here,
and you can see that iPhoto's adopted

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:17.900
Lion's standard new full screen control.

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:20.120
So I'll just take iPhoto full screen.

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:22.270
It's a great way to
look at my photo album.

00:12:22.270 --> 00:12:25.690
If I want to get back to my desktop,
take three fingers,

00:12:25.690 --> 00:12:29.210
and I can just swipe iPhoto
away and back to my desktop.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:32.650
But I didn't have to leave iPhoto
and take it out of full screen.

00:12:32.750 --> 00:12:34.170
It's actually right there.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:36.670
Take a peek at it, go back,
just like that.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:39.860
We love this so much that
we made gestures accessible

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:41.270
in exactly the same way.

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:46.000
Swipe over to the left,
and I have access to my dashboard.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.710
You can see Safari supports
full screen as well.

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:51.320
Let's go take our
Safari window full screen.

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:55.050
So now we have our dashboard over
our desktop over here to the left.

00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:57.880
We have Safari and of course,
iPhoto is still there

00:12:57.880 --> 00:12:59.240
in full screen as well.

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:02.690
You'll notice how Safari is making
great use of all the available

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:04.740
space on the screen for my content.

00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:08.450
But if I want to get at my bookmarks bar,
my menu, just go to the top.

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:11.460
You see they slide right
out like that really nicely.

00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:15.180
And when I want to exit full screen,
I have a control right there in the

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:17.320
upper right animates right back out.

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:19.260
Let's take a look now at Photo Booth.

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:20.860
This is an app.

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:24.730
Absolutely born to run in full screen.

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:28.500
You can see I'm surrounded by
the curtains of the Photo Booth

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:34.590
and in here I can experience some
fantastic new face detection effects.

00:13:34.710 --> 00:13:39.880
So notice as I move,
the birds actually track.

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:48.000
That's the most important
feature in Lion.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.880
And we can also use this face
tracking technology to perform

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:54.360
some targeted facial enhancements.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:56.850
For instance,
I can finally have those big

00:13:56.860 --> 00:13:59.020
eyes that I've always hoped for.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:01.150
So let's take a picture of that.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:03.930
So that's pretty cool.

00:14:04.210 --> 00:14:06.880
So playing around, yeah,
that's great stuff.

00:14:07.270 --> 00:14:10.310
So, you know,
you can spend hours at this.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.440
So full screen is fantastic.

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:14.510
But of course,
Mac users love to do a lot of

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:17.860
things at once and that often means
that they have a lot of windows.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:20.960
In fact, my desktop often looks a
little bit more like this,

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:21.440
right?

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:22.750
I've got a lot going on.

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:26.030
So how do I get across all of
those different activities?

00:14:26.030 --> 00:14:29.340
Well, I just take three fingers,
swipe up on the trackpad,

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:30.980
and I'm in mission control.

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:33.220
From here,
I can get at any window I want.

00:14:33.220 --> 00:14:36.250
So if I want to get at iCal here,
I click, it comes forward,

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:38.280
sweep back into mission control.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:40.810
Over to dictionary, same thing.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:43.930
And across the top,
you see I have my dashboard, my desktop,

00:14:43.930 --> 00:14:45.100
my full screen apps.

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:49.250
So I want to get to iPhoto, just click,
comes forward from anywhere,

00:14:49.250 --> 00:14:52.580
three fingers up,
and I'm back in mission control.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:54.510
I can also quick look my windows.

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:57.950
If I just hit spacebar here,
get a better look at my calendar,

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:01.160
or take this pile of preview
windows and spread them apart

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:02.660
with a little gesture up.

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:07.190
But you know what's really awesome is the
way that multiple desktop spaces are now

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:09.610
integrated right into mission control.

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:13.120
Just take my mouse up to the corner of
the screen and a little space pops up.

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:16.170
I click, I've just created a new space.

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:19.730
